      {
        "id": 2350996,
        "name": "Matthew Hemming",
        "username": "Matthew_Hemming",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/dc4da7/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-02-01T15:07:38.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>This was a very good way to spend Wednesday night and worth travelling to London for, which can\u2019t be said too often!</p>\n<p>Dom Perignon 1996<br>\nQuite evolved on the nose - creamy with some mushroom and truffle action. Perhaps not quite as fresh as a bottle in Singapore last year but shared the same, rich, coffee cream aspect. Delicious interplay between a citric line of acidity and honeyed maturity. 17.5/20</p>\n<p>Chateau Sociando Mallet 1990<br>\nRipe but in a decidedly old school manner of speaking. Starting to show early signs of mature gingerbread notes. Very much at the savoury end of the spectrum and with a hint of hardness toward the finish. Has touches of orange rind VA at the very back. 16/20</p>\n<p>Dominus 1985<br>\nQuite sweet aromas with touches of advanced caramel notes. More cohesive on the palate with marked spice notes and crisp fruit. Has a really firm structural spine still. Taut and firm. Not very giving. 16.5/20</p>\n<p>Flor de Pingus 1996<br>\nWas this the vintage when most of the US allocation ended up in the Atlantic? Distinctive barrel tones of smokey bacon - Taransaud barrels? Heavy oak but matched by deep-pile, deluxe fruit. Balanced despite its considerable girth. Plump black cherry fruit. Serious and impressive. 17.5/20</p>\n<p>Ksara 1991<br>\nWarm, baked fruit aromas. Red fruit and earthy tones. Rounded fruit and supple but overall a bit simple. 15.5/20</p>\n<p>Chateau Musar 1979<br>\nPale and delicate red fruit on the nose. Very sweet and noticeably high toned. Delicate cherry fruit on the back end. Fading but still alive. 15/20</p>\n<p>Chateau Figeac 1961<br>\nSuperb bottle. The bouquet is meaty, composed and spicy. Has more spice on the palate, with significant depth and texture. Mineral, taut, lively and complete. 18/20</p>\n<p>Chateau Leoville Las Cases 1961<br>\nInto decline. Light weight and enervated. 14/20</p>\n<p>Cote Rotie La Mouline 1978 - Guigal<br>\nAmazingly youthful, dark and primary. Floral, multi-faceted and totally harmonious. Complete. Richly-textured. Meaty, spicy and sweet on the finish. 18.5/20</p>\n<p>We finished with a pair of pristine 1976 Hugel SGNs but note taking was replaced by conversation.</p>\n<p>The Guigal lived up to reputation. The Lebanese wines were in honour of our hosts. I\u2019m not a Musar fan and this really didn\u2019t convince me but it was in decent shape for a wine older than me.</p>\n<p>Cheers,<br>\nMatthew</p>",
